83rd OREGON LEGISLATIVE ASSEMBLY--2026 Regular Session
HOUSE AMENDMENTS TO
HOUSE BILL 4061
By COMMITTEE ON ECONOMIC DEVELOPMENT, SMALL BUSINESS, AND TRADE
February 16
1 On page 1 of the printed bill, delete lines 4 through 18 and insert:
2 “SECTION 1. There is allocated for the biennium ending June 30, 2027, from the Admin-
3 istrative Services Economic Development Fund, to the Oregon Business Development De-
4 partment, the amount of $950,000 for the purposes set forth in section 2 of this 2026 Act.
5 “SECTION 2. (1) The Oregon Business Development Department shall establish a pro-
6 gram to award micro-enterprise tariff adjustment grants to small businesses to cover sig-
7 nificant increases in business costs due to tariffs recently imposed by the federal
8 government.
9 “(2) A business is eligible for a grant if:
10 “(a) The business’s headquarters or principal operations are in Oregon;
11 “(b) As of the date on which an application is filed pursuant to this section, the business
12 has been operating for at least two years;
13 “(c) The business has annual sales of not more than $500,000; and
14 “(d) The business can demonstrate a significant increase in business costs due to tariffs
15 recently imposed by the federal government.
16 “(3)(a) The department shall adopt rules to establish an application process, including but
17 not limited to:
18 “(A) An application form;
19 “(B) Information and documentation to be included with the application to establish the
20 business’s eligibility for a grant;
21 “(C) Deadlines; and
22 “(D) Any other provisions the department considers necessary or useful to the applica-
23 tion process or the conduct of the grant program.
24 “(b) A grant may be awarded in an amount not to exceed $10,000 for any business whose
25 application is approved.
26 “(c) The rejection of a grant application may not be appealed, but an eligible business
27 may reapply for a grant at any time.
28 “SECTION 3. Section 2 of this 2026 Act is repealed on January 2, 2029.
29 “SECTION 4. The Oregon Business Development Department, in collaboration with the
30 Port of Portland, the Oregon Tourism Commission, the State Department of Agriculture and
31 other stakeholders selected by the Oregon Business Development Department, shall update
32 the unified trade strategy for Oregon, including, but not limited to:
33 “(1) Identifying opportunities to increase Oregon’s presence in foreign markets, including
34 in-market capacity for emerging markets;
35 “(2) Supporting outbound and inbound trade missions for government and businesses,
LC 189/HB 4061-2

1 including support with aligned messaging;
2 “(3) Promoting Oregon exports and attracting foreign direct investments in Oregon; and
3 “(4) Providing technical assistance to Oregon exporters, including those impacted by
4 tariffs, to support international market access and business expansion.”.
